To create a phase diagram for the staggered six-vertex model with (quasi-)periodic boundary conditions in the critical regime, we can use TikZ to draw the diagram and annotate it with the relevant information. Below is a sample TikZ code that generates a phase diagram with the specified phases and transitions.

```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=5mm]{standalone}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric, arrows.meta}

\begin{document}

\tikzset{
    node distance = 2cm,
    block/.style       = {rectangle, draw, fill=blue!20, 
        text width=6em, text centered, rounded corners, minimum height=4em},
    line/.style = {-stealth', thick},
    cloud/.style = {draw, ellipse,fill=red!20, node distance=3cm,
        minimum height=2em}
}

\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance = 2cm]

\node (phaseI) [block] {Phase I};
\node (phaseII) [block, below left of=phaseI] {Phase II};
\node (phaseIII) [block, below right of=phaseI] {Phase III};

\node (alpha) [cloud, above left of=phaseI, xshift=-1cm] {$0 < \gamma \leq \pi$};
\node (duality) [cloud, above right of=phaseI, xshift=1cm] {Duality Transformation};

\path [line] (phaseI) -- (phaseII);
\path [line] (phaseI) -- (phaseIII);

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
1. **Nodes**: We define three nodes (`phaseI`, `phaseII`, `phaseIII`) representing the different phases of the staggered six-vertex model.
2. **Clouds**: Two cloud nodes (`alpha` and `duality`) represent the anisotropy parameter $\gamma$ and the duality transformation respectively.
3. **Lines**: Arrows connect the nodes to indicate the transitions between phases.

This code will generate a simple phase diagram with the specified phases and annotations. You can further customize the appearance and add more details as needed.

